<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,151,362]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,302,152,176]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Remark.</emphasis>
A very large species easy to identify. Among those species (a smaller part of the known species of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,294,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Teratomyzidae" genus="Poecilovitila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,294,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Poecilovitila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), where first flagellomere sub-spherical (i.e. about as long as high in profile), its ommatrichia less dense and shorter than 
<quantity box="[415,531,223,247]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="0.015">0.015 mm</quantity>
and the lateral light markings of abdomen are very small. Its closest relative is possibly 
<taxonomicName box="[254,411,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Teratomyzidae" genus="Poecilovitila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicornis">
<emphasis box="[254,411,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. brevicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but contrarily to it, its vein R 
<number box="[774,782,275,289]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number box="[791,798,275,289]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" value="3.0">3</number>
only slightly thickened medially (r 
<number box="[1209,1217,275,289]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" value="1.0">1</number>
cell much broader there, than vein R 
<number box="[350,358,314,328]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number box="[367,374,314,328]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" value="3.0">3</number>
(
<figureCitation box="[389,487,298,322]" captionStart="FIGURES 118 – 121" captionStartId="30.[151,264,1655,1678]" captionTargetBox="[405,1180,193,1633]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[405,1181,193,1634]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURES 118 – 121. Wings of Poecilovitila new species. 118 = P. japonica sp. nov.; 119 = P. taiwanica sp. nov., holotype female; 120 = P. thaii sp. nov.; 121 = P. variegata sp. nov. Scales: 1.0 mm each." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203631/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
Fig. 
<number box="[442,487,298,322]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" value="119.0">119</number>
</figureCitation>
). Gena of 
<taxonomicName box="[602,740,300,323]" class="Insecta" family="Teratomyzidae" genus="Poecilovitila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taiwanica">
<emphasis box="[602,740,300,323]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. taiwanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very broad, nearly as the height of first flagellomere.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[197,1292,337,362]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,151,362]" box="[197,1292,337,362]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,332,338,362]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Etymology.</emphasis>
